# Week 4 — Power Pivot & Advanced Excel

This week was focused on Power Pivot and new Excel 365 functions. I learned how to build data models, import and connect multiple tables, define relationships, and create insights using calculated columns and DAX measures. I also explored dynamic Excel functions (`XLOOKUP`, `FILTER`, `TEXTSPLIT`, `SEQUENCE`) that make complex tasks much simpler.

The exercises were more advanced: not just cleaning and merging, but also creating dynamic rankings, conditional formatting, and interactive reports. The week ended with a realistic final case study (accommodation facilities and average prices), where I combined different datasets into a single model ready for analysis.

## Skills developed

- Activating and using Power Pivot in Excel
- Building data models with one-to-many relationships
- Creating hierarchies and slicers to explore data
- Designing DAX measures (dynamic rankings, top N, global averages)
- Using new Excel 365 functions (`XLOOKUP`, `FILTER`, `TEXTSPLIT`, `SEQUENCE`)
- Building advanced PivotTables across multiple integrated sources
- Preparing real-world datasets with Power Query before loading them into the model

## Challenges overcome

- Analyzing global datasets: indicators, countries, continents, and global comparisons
- Creating dynamic country rankings based on selected indicators
- Implementing conditional formatting to highlight performance levels
- Calculating time trends with custom measures
- Using parameters and slicers to enable interactive reporting
- Final project: integrating accommodation facilities and average prices using Power Query + Power Pivot

## Highlight

The most rewarding part was realizing how Power Pivot turns Excel into a real BI tool — connecting multiple tables, enriching them with measures, and building interactive dashboards way beyond classic spreadsheets.
